"
I mean, he\\'s DEATH\\'S BOYFRIEND.
\ That\\'s actually the exact point to which I refer:\ Thanos abandoned his love and need to appease Death during The Infinity Gauntlet. This was clear in anything and everything Starlin wrote following it (starting with Infinity War, which makes it pretty explicit, and was the next writing to feature Thanos \\xb9), but boring, lame-o other writers couldn\\'t be arsed to keep up and went, "What was his thing again...? Oh yeah, he\\'s in love with Death!"\ Starlin brought it up once after that, in The End, in which Thanos has clearly progressed far beyond that, but refers to her as his love all the same--though still in a way suggesting he had moved on, long ago, from pursuing this. She didn\\'t appear at all in what was to be his ongoing series (until Marvel pissed Starlin off for good)--that is, until Keith Giffen took over for the last six issues of it.\ \ I say this with love for Ron Marz (I\\'m a Kyle Rayner fan, even with his writing leading to an infamous comics-critical blog named for an event in *that* story...) and Keith Giffen. But everyone other than Starlin (including those two) tried to boil Thanos back down to a simplistic core: "He\\'s the dude in love with Death!" Though, to be fair, Giffen and Marz at least had a handle on the tenuous nature of his villainy, and even that it was almost abandoned--indeed, Giffen supports his aim to prevent the destruction of the universe as he writes him.\ \ But no, he was the lover of Death. The same as he was once a Darkseid knock-off of sorts. The same as he once pursued power purely for power\\'s sake. \ But those things all changed. Each story Starlin put him through over time gave him more and more dimension--as he asked himself at the end of Infinity War: "And what now are you, Lord Thanos? Hero? Villain? Neither? Maybe just wiser."\ \ It was shameful the way an extremely rounded character kept being sanded back down to two dimensions every time someone else got their hands on him...I actually got into a fight with the editor of Annihilation over this, who told me that the storyline of Thanos in said book was to prevent exactly what I hated: lame writers screwing the character up further (so I apologized).\ \ I grew up going "Oooh! So many characters!!!" when I first saw Infinity War on newsstands, but was taken in by Thanos and his peculiar character, which was neither good nor evil, nor even amoral or simplistically "grey" or antihero. Everyone turning him back into "Oh, he\\'s in love with Death and wants to be with Death," was always such a waste of potential...\ \ \\xb9"Death has rejected me. Like it or not, Thanos of Titan is now one of the living. Life is change.""

(substituting grades for dollars - something closer to home and more  readily understood by all). After the first test, the grades were averaged and everyone got a B. "I know many songwriters (myself included) that feel - for lyric writing especially - that the morning (after you first roll out of bed) is a very free association and productive period. Some songs can happen instantly - but some songwriters might spend the same amount of time on a great song as someone might spend writing a whole book. That all being said - for creative artist type writing - when you have to write something for a film or TV show ASAP, or have a deadline to get a song to an artist - you just have to do it and not make such a big deal out of it all. After you do it a number of times you gain confidence and no longer doubt the inevitable favorable outcome of your efforts - in fact you totally enjoy the intense focus and process. If you are getting freaky, overwhelmed, stressed or grumpy about any aspect - that is writer's stage fright - eventually you will find that to be unnecessary & counter productive.
